## Hard Rules
1. `pact-static-check.sh` must exit 0 before any `.pact`/`.repl` file is considered done.
2. Business state (governance, balances, votes) lives on-chain by default.
3. No architecture change without an ADR — flag the decision before implementing.
4. Ask before acting on anything ambiguous — one question at a time.
5. Flag immediately when any tracked file approaches its size limit.
6. Token discipline: prefer small focused reads; reference ADRs by name, open only when needed.
7. YAGNI ladder (recommended, adjust per team policy) — before writing any code, stop at the
   first rung that holds: (1) needs to exist? → skip and say so; (2) already in codebase? → reuse;
   (3) stdlib/Pact built-in? → use it; (4) already-installed dep? → use it;
   (5) one line? → one line; (6) only then: minimum that works.
   Never cut: input validation at trust boundaries, capability guards, security, data-loss handlers.

## Static Analysis Gate
Every `.pact`/`.repl` change: run `scripts/pact-static-check.sh` (installed at
`~/.claude/scripts/pact-static-check.sh` — copy to your project's CI too).
Must exit 0. Fix all VIOLATIONs before the edit is complete. WARNs: review and disposition.

## Security Review Agent
Before shipping any module: invoke `pact-auditor` sub-agent (`~/.claude/agents/pact-auditor.md`).
Fresh context, no implementation history. Reads code cold. Returns structured findings.
Trigger: "security review", "ready to ship", or explicit pre-deploy request.

